.SH NAME
Bitcoin::Crypto::Script \- Bitcoin Script instance
.SH SYNOPSIS
.IX Header "SYNOPSIS"
.Vb 1
\&        use Bitcoin::Crypto::Script;
\&
\&        my $script = Bitcoin::Crypto::Script\->from_standard(
\&                [P2WPKH => $my_segwit_address]
\&        );
\&
\&        # getting serialized script
\&        my $serialized = $script\->to_serialized();
\&
\&        # getting P2WSH address from script
\&        my $sh_address = $script\->get_segwit_address();
\&
\&        # getting back the address encoded in P2WPKH script
\&        my $address = $script\->get_address();
.Ve
.SH DESCRIPTION
.IX Header "DESCRIPTION"
This class allows you to create Perl representation of a Bitcoin script.
.PP
You can use a script object to:
.IP \(bu 4
create a script from opcodes
.IP \(bu 4
serialize a script into byte string
.IP \(bu 4
deserialize a script into a sequence of opcodes
.IP \(bu 4
create legacy (p2sh), compat (p2sh(p2wsh)) and segwit (p2wsh) addresses
.IP \(bu 4
execute the script
.PP
Note that taproot addresses (p2tr) with script spend paths are created using
Bitcoin::Crypto::Key::Public.
.SH INTERFACE
.IX Header "INTERFACE"
.SS Attributes
.IX Subsection "Attributes"
\fItype\fR
.IX Subsection "type"
.PP
Contains the type of the script, if the script is standard and the type is
known. Otherwise, contains \f(CW\*(C`undef\*(C'\fR.
.PP
\&\fIpredicate\fR: \fBhas_type\fR
.PP
\fInetwork\fR
.IX Subsection "network"
.PP
Instance of Bitcoin::Crypto::Network \- current network for this key. Can be
coerced from network id. Default: current default network.
.PP
\&\fIwriter:\fR \f(CW\*(C`set_network\*(C'\fR
.SS Methods
.IX Subsection "Methods"
\fInew\fR
.IX Subsection "new"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $script_object = $class\->new()
.Ve
.PP
A constructor. Returns a new empty script instance.
.PP
See "from_serialized" if you want to import a serialized script instead.
.PP
\fIopcode_class\fR
.IX Subsection "opcode_class"
.PP
.Vb 2
\&        $class_name = $class\->opcode_class()
\&        $class\->opcode_class\->get_opcode_by_name($opname)
.Ve
.PP
Returns the name of the class used to get the proper opcodes.
.PP
\fIadd_operation, add\fR
.IX Subsection "add_operation, add"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $script_object = $object\->add_operation($opcode)
.Ve
.PP
Adds a new opcode at the end of a script. Returns the object instance for chaining.
.PP
\&\f(CW\*(C`add\*(C'\fR is a shorter alias for \f(CW\*(C`add_operation\*(C'\fR.
.PP
Throws an exception for unknown opcodes.
.PP
\fIadd_raw\fR
.IX Subsection "add_raw"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $script_object = $object\->add_raw($bytes)
.Ve
.PP
Adds \f(CW$bytes\fR at the end of the script without processing them at all.
.PP
Returns the object instance for chaining.
.PP
\fIpush_bytes, push\fR
.IX Subsection "push_bytes, push"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $script_object = $object\->push_bytes($bytes)
.Ve
.PP
Pushes \f(CW$bytes\fR to the execution stack at the end of a script, using a minimal push opcode.
.PP
\&\f(CW\*(C`push\*(C'\fR is a shorter alias for \f(CW\*(C`push_bytes\*(C'\fR.
.PP
For example, running \f(CW\*(C`$script\->push_bytes("\ex03")\*(C'\fR will have the same
effect as \f(CW\*(C`$script\->add_operation(\*(AqOP_3\*(Aq)\*(C'\fR.
.PP
Throws an exception for data exceeding a 4 byte number in length.
.PP
Note that no data longer than 520 bytes can be pushed onto the stack in one
operation, but this method will not check for that.
.PP
Returns the object instance for chaining.
.PP
\fIpush_number\fR
.IX Subsection "push_number"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $script_object = $object\->push_number($int)
.Ve
.PP
Same as \f(CW\*(C`push_bytes\*(C'\fR, but \f(CW$int\fR will be treated as a script number and turned
into a byte representation first. Useful if you have a non\-trivial number that
needs to be pushed onto a stack.
.PP
\fIto_serialized\fR
.IX Subsection "to_serialized"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $bytestring = $object\->to_serialized()
.Ve
.PP
Returns a serialized script as byte string.
.PP
\fIfrom_serialized\fR
.IX Subsection "from_serialized"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $script = Bitcoin::Crypto::Script\->from_serialized($bytestring)
.Ve
.PP
Creates a new script instance from a bytestring.
.PP
\fIfrom_standard\fR
.IX Subsection "from_standard"
.PP
.Vb 2
\&        $object = Bitcoin::Crypto::Script\->from_standard([P2PKH => \*(Aq1Ehr6cNDzPCx3wQRu1sMdXWViEi2MQnFzH\*(Aq])
\&        $object = Bitcoin::Crypto::Script\->from_standard([address => \*(Aq1Ehr6cNDzPCx3wQRu1sMdXWViEi2MQnFzH\*(Aq])
.Ve
.PP
Creates a new object of standard type with given address. The address must be
of the currently default network. In case of \f(CW\*(C`NULLDATA\*(C'\fR, \f(CW\*(C`P2MS\*(C'\fR and \f(CW\*(C`P2PK\*(C'\fR
there is no address, and the second argument must be custom data (\f(CW\*(C`NULLDATA\*(C'\fR),
public key (\f(CW\*(C`P2PK\*(C'\fR) or an array reference with number \f(CW\*(C`N\*(C'\fR of signatures followed
by \f(CW\*(C`M\*(C'\fR public keys (\f(CW\*(C`N\*(C'\fR of \f(CW\*(C`M\*(C'\fR \f(CW\*(C`P2MS\*(C'\fR).
.PP
The first argument can also be specified as \f(CW\*(C`address\*(C'\fR to enable auto\-detection
of script type.
.PP
\fIget_hash\fR
.IX Subsection "get_hash"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $bytestring = $object\->get_hash()
.Ve
.PP
Returns a serialized script parsed with \f(CW\*(C`HASH160\*(C'\fR (\f(CW\*(C`RIPEMD160\*(C'\fR of \f(CW\*(C`SHA256\*(C'\fR).
.PP
\fIget_legacy_address\fR
.IX Subsection "get_legacy_address"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $address = $object\->get_legacy_address()
.Ve
.PP
Returns string containing Base58Check encoded script hash (\f(CW\*(C`P2SH\*(C'\fR address)
.PP
\fIget_compat_address\fR
.IX Subsection "get_compat_address"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $address = $object\->get_compat_address()
.Ve
.PP
Returns string containing Base58Check encoded script hash containing a witness
program for compatibility purposes (\f(CWP2SH(P2WSH)\fR address)
.PP
\fIget_segwit_address\fR
.IX Subsection "get_segwit_address"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $address = $object\->get_segwit_address()
.Ve
.PP
Returns string containing Bech32 encoded witness program (\f(CW\*(C`P2WSH\*(C'\fR address)
.PP
\fIget_address\fR
.IX Subsection "get_address"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $address = $object\->get_address()
.Ve
.PP
This method does not generate P2SH\-type address, but instead returns the
address encoded in the script of standard type. For example, if the script is
of type \f(CW\*(C`P2WPKH\*(C'\fR, then a bech32 segwit address will be returned. If the script
is not of standard type or the type does not use addresses, returns \f(CW\*(C`undef\*(C'\fR.
.PP
Currently handles script of types \f(CW\*(C`P2PKH\*(C'\fR, \f(CW\*(C`P2SH\*(C'\fR, \f(CW\*(C`P2WPKH\*(C'\fR, \f(CW\*(C`P2WSH\*(C'\fR, \f(CW\*(C`P2TR\*(C'\fR.
.PP
\fIget_raw_address\fR
.IX Subsection "get_raw_address"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $raw_address = $object\->get_raw_address()
.Ve
.PP
Same as "get_address", but does not encode the address with base58 / bech32,
and does not add any network markers specific for this type of address. Can be
used to fetch the data encoded in a standard script type, for example output
xonly public key for \f(CW\*(C`P2TR\*(C'\fR.
.PP
\fIoperations\fR
.IX Subsection "operations"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $ops_aref = $object\->operations
.Ve
.PP
Returns an array reference \- An array of operations to be executed. Same as
"operations" in Bitcoin::Crypto::Script::Runner, which is only filled after
starting the script.
.PP
Returned operations are of type Bitcoin::Crypto::Script::Compiler::Opcode.
.PP
Note that operations are returned even for invalid scripts. See "has_errors"
and "assert_valid".
.PP
\fIhas_errors\fR
.IX Subsection "has_errors"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $bool = $object\->has_errors()
.Ve
.PP
Returns a true value if the script is syntax is invalid \- has pushes past end
of the script, opcode errors like unclosed OP_IFs, or opcodes that make it
invalid on compilation like OP_VERIF.
.PP
Note that having errors may not be a good indicator whether the script is
correct, since it may be unconditionally valid due to OP_SUCCESS (in
tapscripts). Script can have errors and still be valid because of that. See
"assert_valid".
.PP
\fIassert_valid\fR
.IX Subsection "assert_valid"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $object\->assert_valid
.Ve
.PP
Checks if the script is valid \- either it has no errors, or it is marked an
unconditionally valid. If the script is not valid, the first error will be
raised as exception. If the script is valid, returns nothing.
.PP
\fIrun\fR
.IX Subsection "run"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $runner = $object\->run(\e@initial_stack)
.Ve
.PP
Executes the script and returns Bitcoin::Crypto::Script::Runner instance
after running the script.
.PP
This is a convenience method which constructs runner instance in the
background. This helper is only meant to run simple scripts.
.PP
\fIis_native_segwit\fR
.IX Subsection "is_native_segwit"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $boolean = $object\->is_native_segwit
.Ve
.PP
Returns true if the type of the script is either \f(CW\*(C`P2WPKH\*(C'\fR, \f(CW\*(C`P2WSH\*(C'\fR or \f(CW\*(C`P2TR\*(C'\fR.
.PP
\fIis_empty\fR
.IX Subsection "is_empty"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $boolean = $object\->is_empty
.Ve
.PP
Returns true if the script is completely empty (contains no opcodes).
.PP
\fIis_pushes_only\fR
.IX Subsection "is_pushes_only"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $boolean = $object\->is_pushes_only
.Ve
.PP
Returns true if the script contains only opcodes pushing to the stack.
.PP
\fIdump\fR
.IX Subsection "dump"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $string = $object\->dump
.Ve
.PP
Returns a readable representation of the script
